🚀 Day 8 — Multilayer Perceptron (MLP) / Artificial Neural Network (ANN) 🎯

Today I started learning Multilayer Perceptrons (MLP) in depth, which are also known as Artificial Neural Networks (ANN). This is an important step because MLPs overcome the limitations of a single perceptron and can handle non-linear problems.

🧠 Key concepts I learned:

🔹 Understanding the Architecture
I studied how to analyze a neural network structure and calculate its weights, biases, and total trainable parameters.

Example architecture:
• Input layer → 4 neurons
• Hidden Layer 1 → 3 neurons
• Hidden Layer 2 → 2 neurons
• Output Layer → 1 neuron

🔹 Calculating Weights and Biases
• Input → Hidden Layer 1
 Weights = 4 × 3 = 12
 Biases = 3

• Hidden Layer 1 → Hidden Layer 2
 Weights = 3 × 2 = 6
 Biases = 2

• Hidden Layer 2 → Output Layer
 Weights = 2 × 1 = 2
 Biases = 1

🔹 Total Trainable Parameters
Total = Weights + Biases
= 12 + 3 + 6 + 2 + 2 + 1 = 26 trainable parameters

🔹 Notation (Very Important for Backpropagation)
To understand deep learning mathematically, I learned how to represent different components:

• Bias (bᵢⱼ)
 b → bias
 i → layer number
 j → neuron number in that layer
 Example: b₁₁, b₁₂, b₁₃ (hidden layer 1), b₂₁, b₂₂ (hidden layer 2), b₃₁ (output layer)

• Output (oᵢⱼ)
 o → output
 i → layer number
 j → neuron number
 Represents the output of each neuron in each layer

• Weights (wᵏᵢⱼ)
 w → weight
 k → layer to which the connection is going
 i → neuron number in previous layer
 j → neuron number in next layer

🔹 Why This Matters
This notation and understanding of parameters is essential for learning Backpropagation, which is the core algorithm used to train deep neural networks.

💡 Key Takeaway:
Today I learned how to break down a neural network into its mathematical components. Understanding weights, biases, and their notation is the foundation for mastering how neural networks actually learn.
